\section*{APPENDIX A}

\section*{Parcel Theory of Gravitational Instability}

Suppose that a weakly stratified ocean is subject to vigorous cooling at the surface over some hundreds of kilometers, producing a density inversion and the possibility of overturning. The fluid cannot simultaneously overturn on this scale; rather, the qualitative response to widespread cooling is one in which relatively small convection cells (plumes) develop. The detailed physics setting the plume scale is as yet unclear, but clearly the
gross transfer properties of the population of convective cells must be controlled by the large scale; the vertical buoyancy flux due to convection must offset loss at the surface. A law of vertical buoyancy transfer for the plume scale and its instability timescale can be developed using parcel theory as follows.

Suppose that the net effect of overturning is to exchange particles of fluid, of density \(\rho_{1}\) and \(\rho_{2}\), over a depth \(\Delta z\). Dense water sinks displacing lighter water below, and releases potential energy to power the plume and flux buoyancy vertically. The change in potential energy \(\Delta P\) consequent on this idealized rearrangement of particles (Fig. 1a) is given by
\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta P & =P_{\text {final }}-P_{\text {initial }} \\
& =g\left[\left(\rho_{1} z_{2}+\rho_{2} z_{1}\right)-\left(\rho_{1} z_{1}+\rho_{2} z_{2}\right)\right] \\
& =\rho_{0} \Delta b \Delta z,
\end{aligned}
\]
where \(\Delta b=\left(b_{2}-b_{1}\right)\) is the buoyancy difference of the particles exchanged over a distance \(\Delta z=\left(z_{2}-z_{1}\right)\), \(g\) is the acceleration due to gravity, and \(\rho_{0}\) is a representative value of the density.

Equating the released potential energy to the acquired kinetic energy of the ensuing convective motion, \(\Delta K= 2 \times(1 / 2) \rho_{0} w^{2}\) (where \(w\) is the vertical velocity scale and there is a factor of 2 because there are two particles), then
\[
w^{2}=\Delta b \Delta z .
\]

Now, if heavy fluid lies above light fluid, an unstable disturbance with growth rate \(\omega\) will develop. Thus, setting \(z \propto e^{\omega t} ; d / d t=\omega ; w=d z / d t=\omega z\), then (A2) implies
\[
\omega^{2} Z^{2}=\left|N^{2}\right| Z^{2},
\]
so
\[
\omega^{2}=\left|N^{2}\right|,
\]
which is the result given by linear stability analysis [in the inviscid limit, the lateral scale of the fastest growing convective mode collapses to zero, no energy is involved in lateral motion, and the limit (A3) is achieved].

The implied vertical buoyancy flux on the plume scale is then, using (A2),
\[
\mathcal{B}_{p}=w \Delta b=\Delta z^{1 / 2} \Delta b^{3 / 2}
\]
which is Eq. (4).

\section*{APPENDIX B}

\section*{Energy Analysis of the Thermal Wind}

We now consider parcels of incompressible fluid at positions ( \(y_{1}, z_{1}\) ) and ( \(y_{2}, z_{2}\) ) in thermal wind balance with a meridional density gradient. The parcels are then interchanged adiabatically (i.e., with conservation of buoyancy).

\section*{a. Potential energy}

The change in potential energy (per unit volume) is again (A1):
\[
\Delta P=\rho_{o}\left(z_{2}-z_{1}\right)\left(b_{2}-b_{1}\right) .
\]

We also have
\[
\Delta b=\frac{\partial b}{\partial y} \Delta y+\frac{\partial b}{\partial z} \Delta z
\]
so that
\[
\left(b_{2}-b_{1}\right)=M^{2}\left(y_{2}-y_{1}\right)+N^{2}\left(z_{2}-z_{1}\right)
\]
if, for simplicity, \(N^{2}\) and \(M^{2}\) are assumed constant and measure the strength of the vertical and horizontal density gradients, respectively.

The slope \(s_{b}\) of a buoyancy surface is, setting \(b_{2}= b_{1}\),
\[
s_{b}=\frac{d y}{d z}=-\frac{M^{2}}{N^{2}} .
\]

Hence, if \(s=\left(z_{2}-z_{1}\right) /\left(y_{2}-y_{1}\right)\) is the slope of the surface along which the particles are interchanged, we may write
\[
b_{2}-b_{1}=N^{2}\left(y_{2}-y_{1}\right)\left(s-s_{b}\right),
\]
so (B1) becomes
\[
\Delta P=\rho_{0} N^{2} \Delta y^{2} s\left(s-s_{b}\right) .
\]

In convectively stable conditions \(N^{2}>0\). Hence, the sign of \(\Delta P\) is the same as that of the factor \(s\left(s-s_{b}\right)\) and it will be negative, corresponding to the possibility of instability, if \(s<s_{b}\), that is, if the slope of the exchange surface has a smaller slope than that of the isopycnals.

\section*{b. Kinetic energy}

We must now consider the change in kinetic energy involved in exchanging fluid parcels. Let us assume a zonal motion \(u=u(y, z)\) of zonal tubes of fluid independent of \(x\) (rather than just parcels) so that zonal momentum cannot be changed by pressure gradient forces. Then we have
\[
\frac{D m}{D t}=0,
\]
where \(m=u-f y\) is the absolute momentum. For any small displacement in the \(y\) direction we must have
\[
\Delta u=f \Delta y
\]
as the change following the motion.
Now consider the change in kinetic energy resulting from the exchange of tubes of fluid with zonal motion \(u_{1}\) at ( \(y_{1}, z_{1}\) ) and \(u_{2}\) at ( \(y_{2}, z_{2}\) ). Then
\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta K= & \frac{1}{2} \rho_{0}\left[\left\{u_{1}+f\left(y_{2}-y_{1}\right)\right\}^{2}\right. \\
& \left.\quad+\left\{u_{2}-f\left(y_{2}-y_{1}\right)\right\}^{2}-u_{1}^{2}-u_{2}^{2}\right] \\
= & \rho_{0}\left(y_{2}-y_{1}\right)^{2} f\left[f-\frac{\left(u_{2}-u_{1}\right)}{\left(y_{2}-y_{1}\right)}\right] .
\end{aligned}
\]

Since
\[
\left(u_{2}-u_{1}\right)=\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}\left(y_{2}-y_{1}\right)+\frac{\partial u}{\partial z}\left(z_{2}-z_{1}\right),
\]
this may be written
\[
\Delta K=\rho_{0}\left(y_{2}-y_{1}\right)^{2} f\left(f-\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}-s \frac{\partial u}{\partial z}\right),
\]
or, since \(f \partial u / \partial z=-M^{2}=N^{2} s_{b}\), then
\[
\Delta K=\rho_{0} \Delta y^{2}\left[f\left(f-\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}\right)-N^{2} s s_{b}\right] .
\]

Hence the change in total energy of the mean motion, \(\overline{\Delta E}\), is, adding (B3) to (B2) and rearranging,
\[
\overline{\Delta E}=\rho_{0} \Delta y^{2} f\left(f-\frac{\partial u}{\partial y}\right)-\frac{f^{2}\left(\frac{\partial u}{\partial z}\right)^{2}}{N^{2}}+N^{2}\left(s-s_{b}\right)^{2} .
\]

\section*{c. Symmetric instability}

Regarding \(s\), the direction of exchange, as a variable, \(\overline{\Delta E}\) has a minimum when \(s=s_{b}\), that is, when the exchange is in the initial isopycnal surface. Then
\[
(\overline{\Delta E})_{\min }=\rho_{0} \Delta y^{2} f^{2}\left(\frac{\zeta}{f}-\frac{1}{\mathrm{Ri}}\right)
\]
will be negative if
\[
\operatorname{Ri}<\frac{f}{\zeta},
\]
corresponding to negative Ertel potential vorticity and the possibility of instability. Here \(\zeta=f-\partial u / \partial y\) is the vertical component of absolute vorticity and
\[
\operatorname{Ri}=\frac{f^{2} N^{2}}{M^{4}}
\]
is the Richardson number.
From (B4) we may again deduce the growth rate:
\[
\omega^{2}=-f^{2}\left(\frac{\zeta}{f}-\frac{1}{\mathrm{Ri}}\right) .
\]

\section*{d. Baroclinic instability}

If the Richardson number of the mean flow is large, then only changes in its potential energy (B2) need be taken into account. For a given exchange distance, ( \(y_{2} -y_{1}\) ), the release of potential energy will be a maximum ( \(-\Delta P\) a maximum) when \(s\left(s-s_{b}\right)\) is a maximum; in other words, when
\[
s=\frac{s_{b}}{2},
\]
then
\[
\begin{aligned}
(\Delta P)_{\min } & =-\frac{1}{4} \rho_{0} N^{2} \Delta y^{2} s_{b}^{2} \\
& =-\frac{1}{4} \rho_{0} \Delta y^{2} \frac{f^{2}}{\mathrm{Ri}}
\end{aligned}
\]

We see that in any region where a thermal wind exists it is always possible to release potential energy for eddy growth provided an appropriate rearrangement of particles takes place.

If an unstable disturbance grows, then \(y \propto e^{\omega t} ; d / d t =\omega ; \boldsymbol{v}=d y / d t=\omega y\). Equating released potential energy to acquired kinetic energy of the eddying motion ( \(\rho_{0} \boldsymbol{v}^{2}\) ) we find, in direct analogy with the upright convection problem outlined above,
\[
\omega^{2} \approx \frac{f^{2}}{\mathrm{Ri}},
\]
which is a heuristic derivation of the growth rate of an Eady wave. Equation (B8) is in effect just (A3) but with the \(\left|N^{2}\right|\) measured along a slope that has one-half that of the isopycnals. Parcel theory has led us to the same result one derives from linear stability analysis.

